        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". For the words, “How do we hear, each of us in our own tongue in which we were born,” which sound abrupt by themselves (with which comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), are, after the long parenthesis, whereby the sense of the sentence is elegantly kept in suspense, resumed in these words, “We do hear them speak,” etc. The language is eminently suited to express wonder. Comp. what we have observed on such parentheses in our comment on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Gregorii Thaum",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Paneg. § 94. The apostles were representatives of a variety both of dialects, for instance, Pontic and Asiatic Greek, and of tongues.",
        "children": []
